@NODE spnote "Notes for this version"

                                    NOTE:

          If you are using v1.05 or earlier, you MUST generate your
         data files again! There are big changes in the way Blitz-CD
                           handles its data files.

                                    NOTE:

       The Italian language file needs the last few lines edited from
                            English to Italian.

                                    NOTE:

               You will need to change lines 6-12, 52, and 77.
            Line 83 holds the values for the @{"main menu commands" link commands}.
                You will need to regenerate your CD's again.



@ENDNODE
@NODE commands "Main Menu commands"

As of version 1.8b, Blitz-CD allows you to set the main menu commands as you
please. Line 83 of the language file holds the menu items as follows:

"ALFHUCSPQ"
 |||||||||
 ||||||||`-Quit Blitz-CD
 |||||||`--Sysop functions
 ||||||`---Search entire CD for file
 |||||`----Change to another CD
 ||||`-----User stats - What can you download?
 |||`------Help with commands
 ||`-------Find a file in current area
 |`--------List/Tag files
 `---------Change current area

Note that no checking is done for duplicate entries.

@ENDNODE
@NODE beat "For the beta testers"

Once again I must thank you all for testing out Blitz-CD. Hopefully all the
bugs have now been squashed.

Blitz-CD no longer uses the test directory. Please read carefully the
importing CD's section to see whats available now.

@ENDNODE
@NODE What " What is Blitz-CD"

Blitz-CD is a program that allows you to set-up your CD's in a manner which
doesn't take up bundles of disk space.

Blitz-CD has the following features:

    o If you only have 1 CD-ROM drive, Blitz-CD will automatically select
      that CD.
    o Will copy the file from the CD to the users private directory. This is
      configurable on a per CD basis.
    o Will not allow users to copy files if it will exceed their file ratio.
    o Will not exceed users directory limit.
    o Will copy the file to a specified path instead of users private
      directory. This is configurable on a per CD basis, and requires the
      user have a batch download capabilities.
    o If copying to a specified path, checks if the file already exists, or
      if a file of the same name but different size exists.
    o Sysop can selectively ban individual users.
    o Checks if the file is already tagged before attempting any file copy.
    o Checks if the user has selected a batch protocol, and warns them not to
      tag files if they haven't.
    o Configurable text and help screen's.
    o Handles multi-line FILES.BBS files.
    o Correctly displays multi-line descriptions.
    o Allows the sysop to easily edit the descriptions.
    o Purges downloaded files copied to an alternate path.
    o Uses smart file copying to reduce CD swapping in stacker units.
    o Searches the entire CD that is currently selected.

@ENDNODE
@NODE xprd "A special warning!"

Sysops who use Gordon Heydon's DLGXPRD as their file transfer handler may run
into problems when using a multi-CD unit such as the Pioneer DRM 60x series.

It appears that DLGXPRD causes the system to crash if a CD gets swapped out
while someone is downloading from it.

This may explain spurious crashes which appear to be Blitz-CD's fault,
although it could be Blitz-CD's fault (Blitz-CD isn't perfect!).

@ENDNODE
@NODE Import " Importing a CD"

Blitz-CD can store its files in 2 places now. The first is 'FILE:Blitz-CD/'
and the second is 'Blitz-CD:'. If you don't want to store your data files in
'FILE:Blitz-CD/', then you can put them anywhere and assign 'Blitz-CD' to
that directory.

From this point on, it is assumed you are using 'FILE:Blitz-CD/'.  If your
using the assignment method, then just replace 'FILE:Blitz-CD/' with
'Blitz-CD:'

To generate the required data files you will need to create a few files.

The first is the CD list.  This file is an ASCII file and is called
'Blitz-CD.List'. It is located in the 'FILE:Blitz-CD/' directory.  It has
the following format:

  Line 1:    Number of CD's available.
  Line 2-11: Lines to remind you of what the following lines mean!
  Line 10+:   Lines are now grouped in groups of 10, 1 group for each CD.

    Line 1:  CD Number. MUST be a unique number which will identify ONE CD.
    Line 2:  CD name (Displayed to users). Maximum length of 30 characters.
    Line 3:  Unique file on this CD. Use CD name instead of device name.
             Ie: Aminet_0693:Aminet.info instead of CD0:Aminet.info
    Line 4:  Low access level for the entire CD. Usefull for X-Rated CD's etc.
    Line 5:  High access level.
    Line 6:  Copy file to alternate directory? 0=No, 1=Yes
    Line 7:  Path to copy file to if appropriate. To copy to users private
             directory, put 'USER:' here.
    Line 8:  Column descriptions start on. This is for the first line of
             the file description, which should also have the filename in it.
    Line 9:  Assume CD is in drive? 0-No, 1-Yes.
    Line 10: A seperater. Just to make changes easier!


Next, to create the data files for each CD in your collection, you need a
control file called 'RAM:Blitz-CD.dat'.  This is a straight ASCII text file.

All operations are done in RAM due to the intensive file activity.

If the CD doesn't have a directories file (such as is on the AmiNet CD), you
can use a disk cataloger to generate a text file of all directories and then
edit this into a suitable format.

The control file has the following form:

  Line 1:     Name of file index list in each directory. Eg: FILES.BBS

This is the actual file list containing file name and description.  It must
have the filename as the first text on the line, and then the description.
If this file contains more than 1 line per entry (for long descriptions),
Blitz-CD will skip the extra lines IF they begin with a <SPACE> character.
You can skip over any header lines in this file by using the value in line 2.

If no such data files are in the directories, Blitz-CD will read in a file
called 'RAM:<Area number>.IDX'.  This file takes the same format as a
'FILES.BBS' file, with the filename followed by 1 or more spaces, followed by
the description.  If doing multiple directories, combine all area's into 1
.IDX file.

  Line 2:     Number of header lines in each file list.

Some index files have info lines at the top. This allows you to
skip these lines.

  Line 3:     General low @{"access level" link access}.  Can be changed for individual areas
              later
  Line 4:     General mid @{"access level" link access}.
  Line 5:     General high @{"access level" link access}.
  Line 6:     Are files in this area to be free? 0=No, 1=Yes.
  Line 7:     Column the description starts on the first line of a
              multi-line description.
  Line 8:     Is file Single line extended. Ie more than 80 characters per
              line, 1 line per file.
  Line 9:     Number of spaces to put before each wrapped line when line 8
              is true.
  Line 10+:   This is the main data line. There will be 1 of these for each
              directory you want scanned in. It has 3 fields:

  Field 1:  Area number.
  Field 2:  Path.
  Field 3:  Area name.

Path may be a maximum of 50 characters!  If this isn't enough, you will have
to make up an assignment for the long directories.

Fields are separated by a space. ONLY the area name may contain spaces!

See the included Blitz-CD.dat file for an example.

Once the control file and the CD list have been created, simply run Blitz-CD
as follows:

  Blitz-CD [K0] [K1]

-K0 and -K1 will turn off the requestor asking if you wish to kill the index
file.  -K0 will automatically NOT kill the file, while -K1 will automatically
kill the file.

You may only work on 1 CD at a time! After each run, copy the files into the
directory 'FILE:Blitz-CD/<CD number>/'.  Copy the .dat files, and the
.Area file.  If you are loading in a BIG CD with many areas, you may need to
manually copy the .dat files while Blitz-CD is running or you may run out of
RAM.

IMPORTANT: Always keep the data file used to generate a CD. You may need
           it again!

During import, you are told if a file cannot be locked onto. The file is
skipped, and the path and name are printed to 'RAM:Blitz-CD.Failed_Locks'.

Also, if a filename is greater than 30 characters, it will not be imported.

VERY IMPORTANT!!

You MUST edit the created <area number>.ASC file to remove any entries
which show up in the failed locks file, and to remove any stray characters at
the end such as ^Z. If you don't, things will get messed up!

VERY IMPORTANT!!

The resulting directory structure will look similar to the following:

FILE:Blitz-CD -- Blitz-CD.HLP
              |- Blitz-CD.List
              |- 1 (Dir) -- 1.dat
              |          |- 2.dat
              |          |- 3.dat
              |          `- Blitz-CD.Area
              |
              `- 2 (Dir) -- 1.dat
                         |- 5.dat
                         |- 20.dat
                         `- Blitz-CD.Area

Produced files during import:

RAM:Blitz-CD.Errors         - Reports program halting errors.
RAM:Blitz-CD.Rep            - Reports each file area imported, and number
                              of files imported.
@ENDNODE

@NODE edit " Editing the Areas and Files"

Blitz-CD allows you to edit individual areas and individual files.

To do this, use the S menu item on the main menu.  The sysop edit menu will
be displayed.

The options are self-explanatory.

NOTE:  When removing a file from an area, you MUST also manually edit the
       index file for that area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Access " Blitz-CD access levels"

Blitz-CD employs 3 access levels for each AREA you create:

       Low access - Minimum level to access a CD.
       Mid access - Minimum level to tag files on CD.
       High access- Maximum level to tag files on CD.

The mid security is set the same way as the low and high security levels are
set.

If a user selects an area in which his access level is between low access and
mid access, they will only be allowed to view the files, and not tag any files
in that area.

During import of a CD, all areas on the CD are set to the same 3 levels as
described in the 'Importing CD' section. If you wish to change these levels
on a per area basis, you will have to edit each individual area.

This feature was requested by a sysop, so its here. If you don't wish to
avail yourself of it, simply set the low and mid values the same.

These access levels can range from 0-255. @{b}NO CHECKING@{bu} is done on the levels,
so make sure they fall in this range.

@ENDNODE

@NODE User " Running Blitz-CD in USER mode"

To run Blitz-CD on-line, call it thus:

    Blitz-CD USER [-M<value>] [-B<value>] [1ONLY] [SHOWCD]
                  [-Z<alt>] [EK] [LOG] [SM] [NODSIZE]

'USER' is a word, not a DLG switch!

-M<value> allows you to set GFA's internal working RAM. This defaults to 64K,
which should be enough for most areas. If you get an 'Out of memory' error
produced, try increasing this a bit. Eg: 'Blitz-CD USER -M100000' to get
100000 bytes of memory. Values less than 1000 are multiplied by 1024.

-B<value> allows you to set the size of the copy buffer used to copy files
from the CD to the HD.  You must choose this number very carefully as it has
a dual function.  It not only provides the buffer size for the copy, but also
provides the output to keep the user aware that something is happening.  If
this allocation fails, the program will exit with a system 'out of memory'
error.  This value defaults to 96K (-B98304)

LOG activates logging.  This will output an entry for each user that enters
Blitz-CD.  To stop mixed-up logs, there is a log file for each port that
Blitz-CD is run from.

Output to the report is that a user has entered, and the details of each file
tagged by the user.

The NODSIZE switch turns off the reporting of the user's private directory
space.

To have 1 copy of Blitz-CD or ConDir running at once, use the 1ONLY switch.
This switch looks for a file 'ENV:ConDir', and if it exists, will exit with a
message. If it doesn't exist, it will create it.

From release 1.1b, the 1ONLY switch's usefulness has been reduced by the
addition of dynamic tag blocking.  This system creates an environment
variable at the start of copying a file, and deletes it when the file has
been copied.  If the copy routine encounters an existing variable, it will
wait, updating the display each second, until the variable is removed.

The EK option is provided in case you wish to have a safety net in case
an error occurs, and the environment variable is not correctly removed. With
this option on, the variable will be killed after 20 seconds of wait time.

The SHOWCD parameter is useful for systems with many CD's, or units such as
the Pioneer 6-pack CD. It will display (in default language):

  Looking for CD's. Please wait ...

and add a dot after each CD is tested.

The -Z<alt> parameter is used to set a different CD list. You may use
anything you like here. For example, using '-AIBM' will look for a CD
list like this:

  FILE:Blitz-CD/Blitz-CD.List.IBM

NOTE: ALL CD's across all lists MUST STILL HAVE A UNIQUE CD NUMBER!

SM invokes a display when loading in a file area.  It will tell you how much
free GFA-RAM is left every 50 files during the load routine. You should run
Blitz-CD in your biggest area with this switch on to determine the value you
need to set for on-line usage.

@ENDNODE

@NODE purge " Running Blitz-CD in purge mode"

It is necessary to purge files from non-USER: alternate holding directories.
This switch makes Blitz-CD scan a data file, checking if each user has
downloaded the file yet, and if so, purges the file.

It takes into account multiple people wanting the same file, and won't delete
it until all have downloaded it.

To run Blitz-CD in purge mode, call it thus:

    Blitz-CD PURGE

'PURGE' is a word, not a DLG switch!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Banned "Banning users"

You may ban individual users from using the program. This is handy for users
who abuse the program.

To ban a user, create a file called "FILE:Blitz-CD/Banned.Users". In this
file resides the names of banned users. The format is 1 name per line in
normal spaced user name (ie not underscored).

@ENDNODE

@NODE help " The On-Line help file"

A file called 'FILE:Blitz-CD/Blitz-CD.HLP.{language}' is accessed for the
on-line help function.  This file can have any of the DLG %-Switches imbedded
within it.

This allows you to have different language files. It uses the first word only
of the language name. Ie for:

  'English with IBM'      use Blitz-CD.HLP.English
  'English with ASCII'    Use as above.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Custom " Customiseable strings in Blitz-CD"

Blitz-CD allows you to change most of the user seen strings in Blitz-CD. This
file MUST be present! It is language changeable. See the @{"on-line help" Link help} section
for instructions on naming the file extension.

This file is called 'FILE:Blitz-CD/Blitz-CD.Lan.{language}'

When running Blitz-CD in import mode from a CLI you MUST have a '.English'
version of strings file!

@{b}ALWAYS@{bu} compare any new release language file with your current file
as lines may be added/deleted. @{b}ALL@{bu} new lines will be added at the
end.

Format of strings:

  <Quote><String><Quote><Operator>

  eg:

    "Press any key"

    This will print 'Press any key' to the screen.

    "%a2Press any key",A

    This will print the same thing, but pass the string through the
    translator, turning the text green if the user has ANSI enabled.

  NOTE: You may have quotes within your text. Blitz-CD only looks at the
        right-most quote. Eg:

    "Press "any" key"

        will be accepted and displayed as you would expect.


Changing the strings:

  All the strings in this file can be changed.

  Strings ending in ',A' will be passed through DLG's TranslateBuffer()
function, meaning you can put ANSI color codes plus other DLG %-Switches.

  Most strings have a pre-defined color, but if you really dis-like the default
color of the text, you can add in a color switch and append ',A' to the end
of the line. The user will still receive the original color code, but it will
be superseeded by your color code.

  NOTE: When importing CD's, no translation's are done. This is because there
        is crucial data missing (user information) which the translator
        requires.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Status " Blitz-CD status"

Blitz-CD is shareware. Without the keyfile, you will get a shareware delay on
start-up, and you will not be able to use Blitz-CD's file copying feature.

Also, only 1 CD can be accessed from each copy of Blitz-CD. If you use
parameters wisely, you can easily get around the last restrictions, the cost
being a menu item for each CD. You might also wish to reword the text sent
when only 1 CD can be found, as this will be sent in the unregistered
version.

As usual, sysop's get full access wether they have the keyfile or not.

Blitz-CD prices:

        $10  - When purchased AT THE SAME TIME YOU REGISTER THE M-TAG
               PACKAGE.
        $20  - When purchased separately.

The keyfile will be sent to you by your preffered method:

        - Crash-mailed to your Fido/AmigaNet node.
        - UUENcoded and E-Mailed to your InterNet address. (Preferred)
        - Put on hold for you on my BBS (Requires you to call and create
                                         yourself an account.)
        - Mailed to you on a floppy disk (Add $2)

All prices are in $US for any currency other than Australian dollars.

Please send only CASH, cheque, or American Express money order.

DO NOT send an International money order!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Future "Whats to come?"

So where does Blitz-CD go from here?

I would like to add in-program downloading of files, and searching of all
CD's. I would also like to add a better way of importing CD's using a GUI.

I am always open to suggestions, so please send them in.

@ENDNODE

